data.body:
I have an extension in the marketplace (gc-excelviewer) that fails to render its virtual document in VSCode 1.9 (Windows or Mac). Some users have reported this issue in 1.8.1 but I have not been able to see it for myself until now.

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Install the gc-excelviewer extension.
2. Open a comma-delimited file with a .csv extension.
3. Click the Open Preview button. The preview tab is created but remains blank.

The problem is that the virtual document's containing <iframe> (with id="_target") has been created with CSS attribute display: none (see [webview-pre.js](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/workbench/parts/html/browser/webview-pre.js)).

Also in that file, in the following code block, newFrame.contentDocument.body is null:

```// workaround for https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/12865
// check new scrollTop and reset if neccessary
setTimeout(function () {
    if (scrollTop !== newFrame.contentDocument.body.scrollTop) {
        newFrame.contentDocument.body.scrollTop = scrollTop;
    }
    document.body.removeChild(frame);
    newFrame.style.display = 'block';
}, 0);
```
As a result, an exception is thrown, the display attribute is never set to block, and the virtual document remains blank. Note that if I tweak this attribute with Chrome Developer Tools then the virtual document renders correctly.

However, I can't implement this workaround in my extension, as the parent <iframe> is not accessible to script code generated by the TextDocumentContentProvider.
